    {
      "id": "cp_ksp2_001",
      "passage": "A chemistry lab studies precipitation of calcium fluoride. Students mix CaCl\u2082 and NaF solutions and compare the ion product Qsp with Ksp for CaF\u2082: CaF\u2082(s) \u21cc Ca\u00b2\u207a + 2F\u207b. The Ksp at the experiment temperature is 4.0 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b9\u00b9.\n\nMixture | [Ca\u00b2\u207a] after mixing | [F\u207b] after mixing | Qsp\n1 | 1.0 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b3 M | 1.0 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b3 M | 1.0 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2079\n2 | 1.0 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2075 M | 1.0 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b3 M | 1.0 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b9\u00b9\n\nThe instructor emphasizes that stoichiometric exponents appear in Qsp and Ksp expressions. Adding a common ion can reduce molar solubility even if temperature is unchanged.",
      "stem": "What is the correct Ksp expression for CaF\u2082?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Ksp = [Ca\u00b2\u207a][F\u207b]\u00b2"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Ksp = [Ca\u00b2\u207a]\u00b2[F\u207b]"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "Ksp = [CaF\u2082]/[Ca\u00b2\u207a][F\u207b]"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Ksp = [Ca\u00b2\u207a] + [F\u207b]"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "A",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Correct. For CaF\u2082(s) \u21cc Ca\u00b2\u207a + 2F\u207b, the solid is omitted and the fluoride concentration is squared because two fluoride ions are produced per formula unit.",
        "B": "The calcium coefficient is one, so calcium is not squared. The exponent follows the balanced equation.",
        "C": "Pure solids are omitted from Ksp expressions because their activity is effectively constant.",
        "D": "Solubility products multiply activities with exponents; they are not simple sums."
      },
      "topic": "Solubility Equilibria & Ksp",
      "difficulty": "Medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "cp_ksp2_002",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "Will Mixture 1 precipitate CaF\u2082?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "No, because Qsp equals zero"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "No, because Qsp < Ksp"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "Yes, because Qsp > Ksp"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Only if CaF\u2082 is a gas"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "C",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "The table gives a nonzero Qsp. Zero would require at least one ion concentration to be zero.",
        "B": "Qsp is greater, not less, than Ksp. A Qsp below Ksp would indicate more solid can dissolve without precipitation.",
        "C": "Correct. Mixture 1 has Qsp = 1.0 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2079, greater than Ksp = 4.0 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b9\u00b9. The solution is supersaturated with respect to CaF\u2082, so precipitation is favored until Qsp falls to Ksp.",
        "D": "CaF\u2082 is an ionic solid in this equilibrium, not a gas."
      },
      "topic": "Solubility Equilibria & Ksp",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "passageRef": "cp_ksp2_001",
