    {
      "id": "cp_ksp2_004",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "Adding NaF to a saturated CaF\u2082 solution will generally:",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "increase molar solubility without limit"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "decrease molar solubility by the common-ion effect"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "remove fluoride from the Ksp expression"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "change the formula to CaF"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "B",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "More common ion suppresses dissolution rather than increasing it without limit.",
        "B": "Correct. Added fluoride is a common ion. Increasing [F\u207b] shifts the dissolution equilibrium left, so less CaF\u2082 dissolves and molar solubility decreases.",
        "C": "Fluoride remains in the Ksp expression; its concentration is exactly what drives the common-ion effect.",
        "D": "The compound formula and dissolution stoichiometry do not change when NaF is added."
      },
      "topic": "Solubility Equilibria & Ksp",
      "difficulty": "Hard",
      "passageRef": "cp_ksp2_001",
      "usePrevPassage": true
    },
    {
      "id": "cp_ksp2_005",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "Why is fluoride squared in Qsp?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Two fluoride ions are produced per CaF\u2082 formula unit"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Fluoride has twice the atomic mass of calcium"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "All anions are always squared"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Calcium is a spectator ion"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "A",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Correct. The exponent comes from the balanced dissolution equation: each CaF\u2082 unit produces two F\u207b ions. Ksp expressions reflect stoichiometry, not atomic mass.",
        "B": "Atomic mass does not determine equilibrium exponents. Stoichiometric coefficients do.",
        "C": "Not all anions are squared; chloride in AgCl would have exponent one. The coefficient matters.",
        "D": "Calcium is part of the equilibrium and appears in the expression with exponent one."
      },
      "topic": "Solubility Equilibria & Ksp",
      "difficulty": "Medium",
      "passageRef": "cp_ksp2_001",
